2
Events are things that happen that other things might want to know about.  More specifically, they're broadcasts of $action objects.  Your own objects can listen for these broadcasts and react to them.
2
The chain starts when an object calls $room:broadcast_event().  Objects that use the queueable $action system don't even have to do this -- the action queue system sends these broadcasts automatically.  If your action never passes through the action queue (like social verbs, talking, etc.), you'll have to announce your action yourself by calling location:broadcast_event(1, OBJ action, OBJ source, LIST args).
2
The room then does a few things.  First, it looks for :hear_event() on every object in the room -- if it exists, it calls it, passing it all the arguments passed to :broadcast_event().  Next it looks for :hear_event_eventname() (where eventnname is the name of the action object we were passed).  If that exists, it also calls that.
2
This way, you can make an object that listens for just one or two types of events by writing specific :hear_event_eventname() verbs on your object.  Or, if for some reason you need to look for all events, or broad classes of events, you can still write a general :hear_event() verb.
2
To get a complete list of possible events you can listen for, look at @kids $action.  If you want to listen for a custom event type, you can simply create a child of $action for that purpose, and pass that when you need to broadcast that event's occurence.
