2
@tasks / @killtasks
2
(on Eazy's FO, #91479.)
2

2
@[kill]tasks [-f] [-t] [<task-ids>] [for <programmer>|prog:<prog>] [this:<object>|on a <parent>] [verb:<verbname>] [obj:<verbloc>|from <verbloc>|from a <parent>]
2

2
List all currently queued (suspending) tasks, filtered by the given criteria and by some built-in filters. If you are using this command you probably know what it all means -- but if you don't, each line represents an executing verb which has called yield or suspend for some reason and is waiting. These are tasks. Each task has a specific time to start (TTS) which it is waiting for, and when that time arrives it would like to run. Unfortunately, we only have one MOO, so only one verb can actually run at a time. So we have a task queue, which is what you can see with @tasks.
2

2
Tasks with a negative TTS have been denied the ability to run and are behind schedule. This only happens when the MOO is overly busy and is generally a signal that something is wrong. [Note: tasks waiting for input (see 'help read()') are always shows as behind, but can be safely ignored and are usually filtered out.]
2

2
Options:
2
  -f   disable built-in filters
2
  -t   show tasks more than 120s away
2

2
<task-ids> can be a task id or abbreviated, @forked/@kill style, with a %.
2

2
If you are using @killtasks, you will see a list and be prompted before any tasks are actually killed.
2

2
Examples:
2
  @tasks for me                    -- tasks that are your fault
2
  @tasks -f -t                     -- everything. oh god
2
  @tasks obj:$heart                -- all $heart verbs
2
  @tasks on a $player              -- verbs in which 'this' is a player
2
  @tasks verb:queue on an $npc     -- verbs where 'this' is an $npc and contain 'queue'
2
  @tasks %362                      -- task ids ending in 362
2
  @killtasks prog:eazy             -- eazy messed up again
2

