30
2
-cputime-
2

2
CPU time, as reported by cputime(), task_stack() and callers(), is always in milliseconds, supplied by the server's OS. On some machines it is rounded to the nearest 4ms, on other machines it's totally useless, but it is the best we can do.
2

2

2
If you're looking at cputime(), it includes:
2
 - the cpu time spent processing the verb you're in
2
 - the cpu time spent in every verb that's been called so far by this verb.
2

2
It DOES NOT include any cpu time spent in any verb that's called your verb.
2

2

2
IF you're looking at task_stack() or callers(), you get a different CPU time for each frame in the stack.
2

2
A stack with cputime looks like this, more or less:
2

2
    this, verb name,              prog, vloc,player, line, cputime
2
1. {$cu, "suspend_if_needed",   #45097,  $cu, #7195,   12,       0}
2
2. {$lu, "count_list_suspended",  blah, blah,  blah,    7,      50}
2
3. {#538, "items_and_counts",     blah, blah,  blah,   24,    1245}
2
4. etc
2

2
This is made up, but if it was a real stack, it would mean that:
2
 - In #538:items_and_counts, 1245ms of CPU time was spent executing everything in that verb up to the point it called $lu:count_list_suspended on line 24.
2
 - Then, in $lu:count_list_suspended, 50ms of CPU time was spent running everything up to the point it called $cu:sin on line 7.
2
 - Zero ms (or close enough to zero) of CPU time were spent running things in $cu:sin up until the call to suspend().
2

2
By looking at all the cputimes in a stack, you can get a full picture of how much cpu time was spent at each layer of a task.
2

2
Note that the cputimes in the stack are the same numbers you would get if you called cputime() at the given points in each verb in the stack.
