2
A new data type on MOO 1.9 (Hell variant) is the hash, an associative array. This means it maps 
2
unique keys to values. This is different from the normal type of array, which is merely a list 
2
of values.
2

2
Hash variables are created, set, and accessed in ways similar to lists:
2

2
    "Create an empty hash";
2
    my_hash = [];
2
    
2
    "Create a hash with stuff in it";
2
    my_hash = ["key" -> 7, "other key" -> 26];    
2
    my_hash["another key"] = 100;
2
    
2
    ;my_hash["key"]
2
     => 7
2

2
Hashes have type HASH.
2

2
    ;typeof([]) == HASH
2
     => 1
2

2

2
Hashes can deal with many different data types.
2

2
          Keys:   STR, OBJ, INT, FLOAT, or ERR
2
          Values: ANY (including HASH)
2

2
    my_hash = ["str" -> 1, #98 -> ["name" -> "Gilmore"], 7.2 -> "hamburgers", 2 -> 2];
2

2
And of course you can construct them with variables:
2

2
   a = "foo"; b = 2;                          x = {"bar", 7};
2
   my_hash = [a -> b];                        my_hash = [x[1] -> x[2]];
2

2
You can use them in loops...              You can test for membership....
2

2
    for entry in (my_hash)                    if ("key" in my_hash)
2
       {key, value} = entry;                      player:tell("key is in hash!");
2
       player:tell(key, " is ", entry);       endif
2
    endfor
2

2
And you can use new builtins on them!
2

2
  hashremove(["key" -> 1], "key")         hash({"key", 1}, {"otherkey", 2})
2
   => []                                   => ["key" -> 1, "otherkey" -> 2]
2
   
2
  keys(["ham" -> 1, "burger" -> 2])       values(["ham" -> 1, "burger" -> 2])
2
   => {"ham", "burger"}                    => {1, 2}
2

2
For more help on builtins, see 'help <functionname>'.
2
For a quick review of this in the future, see 'help hashes'.
29
5
4
27
2
Quick reference for hash variables:
2
   keys: STR,OBJ,INT,FLOAT,ERR  values: ANY    typeof is: HASH
2
   
2
   literal hashes: [key -> value, key -> value, ...] or []
2
   
2
   read values:     set values:           delete keys:
2
     h[key]            h[key] = value       h = hashremove(h, key)
2
   
2
~1b[31mDO NOT do this:~1b[0m
2

2
~1b[31m   for entry in (h)                key in h~1b[0m
2
~1b[31m     "entry == {k, v}";             => 1 or 0~1b[0m
2
~1b[31m   endfor~1b[0m
2

2
Looping over a hash does not yet work. It will crash the whole MOO! Instead, do this:
2

2
   for entry in (keys(h))
2
     "h[entry] == v";
2
   endfor
2

2
This is just looping over a regular list, which is fine.
2
   
2
   from lists:
2
      l = { {"k", 1}, {"k2", 2}, {"k3, 3" };
2
      h = hash(@l);
2

2
   also:  keys(h) => list of keys      values(h) => list of values.
29
5
4
11
2
Syntax:   hash( LIST entry1, LIST entry2, ... LIST entryN ) => HASH
2

2
  Returns a hash created with entries as the given lists.
2

2
  Each entry must be of the form {key, value}.
2
  Keys may only be STR, OBJ, INT, FLOAT, or ERR.
2

2
Errors:
2
  E_TYPE:   an entry wasn't a LIST, or a key wasn't one of the 
2
            types listed above.
2
  E_ARGS:   an entry list was not size 2.
