http://hellmoo.org/wiki/index.php/Timeline
361
5
4
13
2
Good morning! It is 8:00 AM. You are in your clone tube, suspended in a cold blue slime, with the visions of being shot to death still fresh in your head. Between the grasp the pills have on you, and the disorienting cloning process, your brains are absolutely fried. The few childhood memories of the days before the Collapse are just fragments of a pleasant dream. The last time life seemed worth living was about seventy years ago. The air raid sirens debuted a new tune that day, their falsetto doomsday song in perfect harmony with your confused crying, as your father refused the neighbors entry into the fallout shelter in your backyard. There was a gust of malevolent wind and a loud pop, and the world turned to shit.
2

2
Nobody was ever sure of what had happened, other than the obvious - life was over. Since that day, it was as if you had died with the other ninety-six percent of the Earth's population, and been chosen to serve time in a cruel purgatory; a penance for your membership in the society that ended civilization and scarred the earth. You travelled the wastes in a confused trance as the survivors of the atom war crawled back up upon mutated feet, desperate and angry. Wrath begat wrath, and the wars started again, battles for clean water and untainted supplies - you went on to shoot your first gun at 13, kill a man at 14, and finally succumbed to misery and hatred, failing a series of half-assed suicide attempts at 17.
2

2
You found yourself in a tough spot one day after a real rager of a crank binge, sprawled on a strech of highway after getting hit by a band of doped-up raiders. They had stripped you of anything of worth and left you to die, after one of their bullets bore into your left temple and ricocheted around in your skull. You looked to the sky, and though your body felt cold and distant by that point, you began to weep, knowing that glorious death was near, and this time it would be final. Luckily, a group of people in the bureaucratic recruitment outfit divisions of the Weyland-Utani corporation came upon your twisted body and offered you salvation(1) on earth, if you subjected yourself to the cloning process and join them in a new city, the framework for the reincarnation of the pre-Collapse days. They presumed your silent weeping and twisted looks of anguish as agreement to this new arrangement.
2

2
Weyland-Utani needed new customers; with all the babies yanked out of weeping mothers turning out to be stillborn, they instituted the mandatory clone vats to ensure mankind would be on earth to keep them in business indefinitely. They arranged for you to join the other happy survivors within Freedom City, where there is a surveillance camera for each person, and three people monitoring each camera. Life was bearable for a while; you did what the corporations said and you were paid fairly, and you always had the unveiling of the new Spring line of automatic weapons and skimpy thong underwear to look forward to. Decades passed as if hours, the clone vats kept you young, and fast from the clutches of eternal rest.
2

2
You quickly became aware of how unpleasant your new situation was. The corporations ran Freedom City with an iron fist, a crime such as petty larceny could get you stuck with six months of hard labor to a half dozen death sentences, to be served at the overzealous police department's earliest convenience. Your neighbors were not friendly; Slagtown and Gangland harbored criminals and miscreants deemed unusable by the Freedom City Wellness Committee, while the technofreaks of Maas Neotek and the insane jihadists of New Clearwater worked on interesting ways to kill you, and each other, every day. Weyland-Utani's Contamination Hazard & Urban Disposal operation had backfired terribly, spawning a race of mutant sewer dwellers in the streets below you, while even worse things lurked deeper in the subways, and beneath them laid a vast tunnel network, the nest of a race of creatures belched up from the worst dregs of Hell. This is the world you have inherited; you are doomed to haunt it forever.
2

2
You are a consumer first and a soldier second, gifted with the opportunity to die every death imaginable. The glory of capitalism keeps you immortal and the genius of neo-science keeps you strong. Your daydreams are cut short as the bottom of the clone vat opens up beneath you, sending you into the world again, cold and naked. Another day, another dollar.
2

2
(1) Your salvation may vary. Terms are subject to change at any time. Weyland-Utani is a subsidiary of MONDOCorp. MONDOCorp: Without Us, You're Dead.
361
5
4
37
2
In the apocalyptic world of tomorrow, the world has only one thing in common: the money system. (That, and mutants roam everywhere, and you can fight anybody and anything, but bear with me, okay?)
2

2
In HellMOO, no one has any paper cash, and rarely do people barter. Instead, there is but one currency, and that is digital credits.  To use credits, every human has a wristpad that displays credits and allows transfer of them between wristpads (and can tell time, give you a map of the area, but let's focus on the money part.)
2

2
To take a look at how much money you have, type 'su'.  This is like 'st' but much shorter!
2

2
[|||||||||||||| ] XP: 2071 $31,400
2

2
Your health, spendable XP, and money are shown in that order.
2

2
Money is used for a lot of things; usually, you'll use it to buy stuff from merchants. To buy something, go in their store and type 'list' to see what they have to offer. To actually buy something, type 'buy <item>' and, if you have enough credits, you'll buy it.   You can also buy things from automats; if you find one, 'exam automat' to find out how to use it.
2

2
Money is useful for lots of other things -- learning skills from NPC teachers, paying Kharn not to cut your head off and fuck the stump...the list goes on.  To pay a human player, type 'pay <amount> to <player>'.  If the player isn't actually in the room, use 'paypal <amount> to <player>' -- unfortunately paypal takes a 5% transaction fee.  Jerks!
2

2
So, how do you earn money? Lots of ways.
2

2
There are numerous NPCs walking in town. Go up to them and ask what they need.
2

2
'-69Jane Whaddya need?'
2
Casull [to 69Jane]: Whaddya need?
2
69Jane [to Casull]: I could use a cigarette, I need a screw, I could use a new TV, I'm hungry, and I got places to be, ya know.
2

2
Supply any of their needs and they'll usually pay you.  If you prefer not to make an honest buck, you can always try running a scam on someone.
2

2
You can scavenge for loot to sell -- this can be quite profitable early in the game.  Check the crack mansion, Sharpton Projects, gangland, the sewers, and many other locations until you've found the best spots.
2

2
Upstairs in Any Port is Fat Ratzo. Fat, ugly, and probably piggy, but he's got jobs for you. Ask him about jobs; he could always use someone to deliver packages, and there're always some (possibly easy) bounties to kill for good cash.
2

2
Or take a job with the ENEMA corp.  MServo hangs out at the museum and is happy to hire any new players.
2

2
Of course, you're not limited to just these methods. Go ahead, check out the town. You never know. (But you can't steal cash, [un]fortunately.)
2

2
Summary:
2
- All money is in your wristpad
2
- type 'su' or 'st' to see how much money you have
2
- Use money to buy shit and learn skills from NPCs
2
- Get money by selling junk
361
5
4
25
2
Congratulations! You have just died somehow, either because someone killed you, you killed yourself, a disease wiped you, etc. The question is, now what?
2

2
Well, I hope you first updated your clone before you died. Think of updating your clone as saving your game: If you die, your character goes back to that point. When you first start in HellMOO, you have a clone already created for you, so if you die, you won't go back to the Dream World. How convenient!
2

2
Of course, you want to keep your clone updated as often as possible. A good idea to update your clone is when you've used all your available IP for the day, when you get a major XP boost from killing a lot of enemies, before you go exploring-yeah, like I said, keeping your clone updated is a good idea. Of course, it costs money to keep your clone updated, and that cost rises as you gain XP. (If it were free, I'd update my clone multiples times every visit from paranoia.) To update yourself, go to Clone Arrangers (CA on the map) and type 'update' . Quick and easy.
2

2
Dying also costs money; to resurrect yourself, you have to pay double the cost of updating, along with 10XP, plus you revert back to your last-updated clone. Fortunately, it's not so easy to die at higher levels, but the cost gets steeper. If you don't have enough money to pay for resurrection, you simply pay for it with a higher XP cost.
2

2
And that's why dying sucks, but it doesn't suck too hard if you update often.
2

2
Death won't necessarily set you back completely...hell, you might not even have to clone yourself. If you're lucky, someone will have seen you die, and they'll have a defibrillator on them, which can wake you up from your dead state. You won't be able to page anyone inside the afterworld, but you can use chatnet or corpchat to revive you, assuming your body hasn't rotted yet. Just remember that using either of them can mean that someone will come to your body to loot your corpse. And people will do so. Use your judgement before you decide on doing that.
2

2
Finally, with the clone arrangers, you can delete your clone if you feel like starting your character over again. Just go to the Clone Arrangers, type 'delete', and die. Next time, you'll be in Dreams of Before.
2

2
Summary:
2
- Update often!
2
- CA on the map deals with all clone business
2
- When in CA, type update to update your clone
2
- In CA, type delete to delete your clone to start anew
2
- Updating costs money, cost increases with XP
2
- Death costs double that of update cost, along with 10XP
2
- If you can't pay the cost of death, you lose more XP than usual
2
- You can hope someone will revive you with the defib
2

2
See also: help rage
