A room is considered "public", generally speaking, if creatures can wander into it. To find out if the room you're in is marked public, look at the icon in the middle of your minimap. If it's light blue, you're in a public place. If it's red, you aren't.
2

2
This is important for skill training -- most skills can't be improved through practice in a non-public place.
361
5
4
23
2

2
If an exit is marked in red, it means you have to climb to go that way. By looking in that direction, you can tell if it's a climb up or down, the distance of the climb, the difficulty of the climb, and whether or not there's a rope. If you decide you want to try the climb, just move in that direction normally and the climbing will begin.
2

2
Entering stop climb will stop your climbing and drop you from where you are. A fall from even a few meters up can hurt you, break bones, and even cause brain damage or death.
2

2
Eschaton Outfitters (EO) in FC sell two helpful items: climbing ropes and grappling hooks. Climbing ropes make a climb easier, but can only be hung down from the top of a climb with 'hang rope from <exit>'. Grappling hooks can be thrown to the top of a climb, but are significantly more expensive.
2

2
To throw a grappling hook to an exit above you:
2

2
'throw grappling hook to <exit>'
2

2
To attach a rope or grappling hook to an exit below you:
2

2
'attach rope to <exit>'
2

2
You can recover a rope or hook by entering:
2

2
'detach <item> from <exit>'
2

2
You can improve your climb skill by, well, climbing. Rolf's Gym (RG) in Slagtown has a climbing wall. You can also learn climb from Smokey, who runs EO. Some mutations will also give a bonus to climb.
2

2
Happy climbing!
