You can control what you allow other players to do to you with the 'allows' command. Try just typing 'allows' by itself. You'll see a list of what you do and don't allow other people to do.
2

2
You can allow a particular person by name (or simply "friends" (see: help friends) or "everyone") to do the following kinds of things to you:
2

2
cocoon - Let them open your cocoon. (see help cocoons)
2
gifts - Let them give you things.
2
medical - Let them heal you.
2
rape - Let them grab you.
2
sex - Let them fuck & suck & fondle you.
2
visit - Let them enter your apartment.  Anyone you haven't allowed this to will be committing a crime if they enter your home.
2

2
To allow someone to do something, just type something like 'allow cocoon from FriendlyGuy'.  To take it back, 'deny cocoon from FriendlyGuy' . Remember, allows by itself will show everything you allow or deny.
2

2
Keep in mind there's a reason this system exists -- most of these actions could injure or even kill you if done by a malicious person! Don't allow people to do things to you just because they asked.
361
5
4
7
2
You can store a list of friends, the primary purpose of which is to assist in specifying permissions (see help allows).  For example you may want to allow your friends to help you: 'allow medical from friends' ).
2

2
With no arguments, 'friends' will simply show you a list of your friends.
2

2
You can add a friend with the command 'friend +name' , where name is the name of the player you want to add as a friend.  Should one of your friends turn out to steal your drugs or get a handjob from your mother, you can remove the jerk with the command 'friend -name'.
2

2
If you wanted to know how to MAKE friends, well...that's tricky.  Try hanging out in Any Port and chatting folks up.  Or saying hello to someone on the street.  Not EVERYONE in Hell is a slavering bloodthirsty psychopath.  Even so...don't trust em as far as you could kick em (that isn't far at all).
