2
In the lawless world of tomorrow, anyone can, in theory, attack anyone at any time. With that knowledge, the Freedom City government, sponsored by Weyland-Utani corporation, has set up a monitoring system all over Freedom City's central area. Copying this blueprint, other places have also set up their own fast-acting security network, including the apartment buildings, Corpclave, Weezer Dam, and very important businesses.
2

2
What this means for you, the citizen, is that you *absolutely should not* attack anyone within Freedom City's boundaries. Aggressive actions, including grabbing (and raping) other citizens, will cause you to earn stars. (You won't earn stars for retaliating against scum, like chomologists and dogs.) Earn four or more stars and the police will send their units after you: First the K-9s for minor infractions, followed by the stronger C3-50s, followed by the all-powerful McBain, who will wipe the floor with you, guaranteed. (Other areas may have different police units.) If you die while you have stars, you will reclone in Panopticon Prison, which is a terrible, terrible place to be: Nothing to do while you wait for your stars to drop, and no safe place to log out, meaning you're basically fair game.
2

2
The simplest way to avoid getting stars is to just not aggress anyone in Freedom City. Don't be an idiot and attack willy-nilly or you'll end up in prison real quick.
2

2
Of course, we all make mistakes (or we're just highly stressed and can't take it any more.) If you do happen to get stars (accidentally, we're hoping!), note that your stars will go down slowly (based off of your XP and reputation with the FCPD, among other things). Stars will also go away faster in prison than out on the street. Ideally, you want to run as far away from the offending area as possible (IE if you've got K-9s all over you, get out of the greater Freedom City area. If you've got apartment bots all over you, get out of the apartment building.) If you do get caught and you land in prison, well, you'll just have to kill the time till you can get out.
2

2
If you get stars often enough, for severe enough crimes, you'll build up a reputation with the police force, which decays slowly over time.  As this reputation rises, you'll find that you get more severe responses coming at you for crimes.  One should consider this before one goes career criminal.
2

2
See also: help prison, help etiquette
361
5
4
11
2
Repairing things is a valuable skill used to fix up shit when it breaks. And shit will break. Repairing things depends on your repair skill, which depends on your brains. To repair something, simply type 'repair <item>'.
2

2
Repairing is separated into three general categories: Broken weapons, worn-down armor, and anything else.
2

2
For weapons, there's a whole section dedicated to it; see help weapon-repair.
2

2
Armor is an interesting thing to repair. Armor has HP, and the lower the HP value, the less protection it offers. When the armor's HP gets to 0, the armor will break, leaving you armorless. Repairing your armor will restore it to max health, but its max health will be lowered by 1, so eventually you will have to replace that armor (though not for a long while.) Be careful when repairing armor, too: If you *really* suck at repairing armor, you'll destroy the armor a bit more, taking a way a hit point. To see how much HP the armor has, wear it and type 'worn'.
2

2
Repairing anything else is quite easy, since you don't have to worry too much about it breaking all the way from your failed repairs. Anything in a very smashed state is pretty unusable, so if someone smashes in your door, you won't be able to close it till you repair it a bit. Definitely keep that repair skill up, unless you're willing to pay for a repair every time.
2

2
Related: help weapon-repair
