2
Emoting is the term for any kind of posing action which makes your character do something non-functional in the room, like smiling, laughing, nodding, etc. There are several ways to do this.
2

2
The simplest is to just type various emote commands (also sometimes called socials) -- there are hundreds of these, including: 'smile, laugh, grin, burp, eye, stare,' etc. Some are obvious, and some are hidden easter-eggs. Most can be given a target, like 'smile Gilmore' to smile at Gilmore.
2

2
Another easy way is to use the : command, aka 'emote'. Typing this:
2

2
':points at the dead chobo and laughs!'
2

2
would produce in your location the text:
2

2
Gilmore points at the dead chobo and laughs!
2

2
Note that this command simply reproduces whatever text you give it -- the above would work even if there's no dead chobo in the room. You're probably thinking, Hey I could use this to fool people! You probably could; for instance you could emote pulling a grenade. Doing this is considered very rude and lame. If we hear of you acting like an idiot in this way, you'll probably be sorry you thought of it. Just don't.
2

2
There's also the . command, aka 'pose'. Typing this:
2

2
'.point at dead and laugh'
2

2
would produce in your location the text:
2

2
Gilmore points at the dead chobo and laughs!
2

2
Unlike emote, the pose command DOES check for objects in the room that match what you type, and attempts to convert verb tenses and so forth to make a sensible message. Experiment with it to find out more about how it works.
2

