Emoting is the term for any kind of posing action which makes your character do something non-functional in the room, like smiling, laughing, nodding, etc. There are several ways to do this.
2

2
The simplest is to just type various ~1b[1memote~1b[22m ~1b[1mcommands~1b[22m (also sometimes called socials) -- there are hundreds of these, including: ~1b[1m~1b[37msmile, laugh, grin, burp, eye, stare,~1b[22m~1b[36m etc. Some are obvious, and some are hidden easter-eggs. Most can be given a target, like ~1b[1m~1b[37msmile Gilmore~1b[22m~1b[36m to smile at Gilmore.
2

2
Another easy way is to use the : command, aka ~1b[1m~1b[1m~1b[37memote~1b[22m~1b[36m.~1b[22m Typing this:
2

2
~1b[1m~1b[37m:points at the dead chobo and laughs!~1b[22m~1b[36m
2

2
would produce in your location the text:
2

2
Gilmore points at the dead chobo and laughs!
2

2
Note that this command simply reproduces whatever text you ~1b[1mgive~1b[22m it -- the above would work even if there's no dead chobo in the room. You're probably thinking, Hey I could use this to fool people! You probably could; for instance you could ~1b[1memote~1b[22m pulling a grenade. ~1b[1mDoing~1b[22m this is considered very rude and lame. If we hear of you acting like an idiot in this way, you'll probably be sorry you thought of it. Just don't.
2

2
There's also the . command, ~1b[1maka~1b[22m ~1b[1m~1b[37mpose~1b[22m~1b[36m. Typing this:
2

2
~1b[1m~1b[37m.point at dead and laugh~1b[22m~1b[36m
2

2
would produce in your location the text:
2

2
Gilmore points at the dead chobo and laughs!
2

2
Unlike ~1b[1memote,~1b[22m the ~1b[1mpose~1b[22m command DOES check for objects in the room that match what you type, and attempts to convert verb tenses and so forth to ~1b[1mmake~1b[22m a sensible message. Experiment with it to find out more about how it works.
