2
The 'gear' command, as you might have noticed, spits out a whole bunch of juicy numbers.  What's it all about?
2

2
The top section lists your armor, one bodypart per line.  Each column shows the armor's resistance, or "soak", to a particular kind of damage.  This is your total soak for that damage type at that bodypart, added up from all pieces of armor covering that location, PLUS any soaks your mutated skin might have.  Below, your total dodge penalty from your armor is shown.
2

2
The next section lists every weapon you're carrying (wielded weapons first), and the following stats for each:
2

2
- 'Raw' : The range of raw skill at which this weapon is effective.  If your raw is below this, you'll be at a penalty to hit.  If above, you won't be able to earn IP using this weapon.
2
- 'Hit' : Your effective hit skill with this weapon.  Higher hit means more and better hitting!
2
- 'Spd' : Your effective speed with this weapon, in seconds.  Lower is faster!
2
- 'Par' : The weapon's parry class.  Higher parry means more parrying!
2
- 'DType' : Type of damage.  For weapons with split damage, each type is listed on its own line.
2
- 'base' : The weapon's intrinsic base damage.
2
- 'effec' : Your effective damage with this weapon.
2
- 'crit%' : How often you'll land those delicious criticals.
2
- 'eDPS' : An estimate of how much damage per second you might do against an unarmored enemy.
2

2
Check your 'gear' display when you find new weapons, or when your weapon changes through damage or modification, to keep up on how it's going to perform for you.  Remember that weapons and armor have many more properties than are shown in 'gear', so always let your own observations and experience be your guide to what works.
