2
There are times when you need to hold something in your hands, other than your primary weapon, while in dangerous territory, like if you're healing up in between fights.  What if something hostile attacks you while you're caught off-guard?
2

2
For situations like these, there is the 'ready' command.
2
By typing one of the following commands, you'll perform certain actions the next time something confronts you.
2

2
'ready <item>'               will autowield <item>.
2
'ready <item> and nothing'   will autowield <item> and unwield anything else you may be holding.
2
'ready <item> and <item>'    will autowield <item> and <item> both at the same time.
2
'ready fists'                will unwield anything you're holding.
2

2

2
'ready <item> and nothing'   is helpful in situations where you forget to unwield your butcher knife or such.
2
'ready <item> and <item>'    is ideal for those who dual wield.
2
'ready fists'                is ideal for those who prefer to use their own two (or three) fists (or claws) in combat.
2

2
If you need to remind yourself what you've readied, type 'ready' by itself.
2
To unset your readied item(s), type 'ready clear'.
