Tags are personal aliases for objects, players, and NPCs in the game. You can tag pretty much anything, and then your tag will work just like any alias or name for that object.
2

2
Commands:
2
  'tag <anything> with <word>'     -- add a tag
2
  'tags'                           -- list all of your defined tags
2
  'rmtag <word> from <anything>'   -- remove a tag from one thing
2
  'deltag <word>'                  -- delete a tag completely
2
  'tagrename <oldtag> to <newtag>' -- rename a tag
2

2
The '<anything>' in the tag command can be:
2
 a) an object/player name in the room with you
2
 b) 'player <playername>'
2
 c) the special phrase 'all players'.
2
 d) 'this <object>', for when you just want THIS instance of an object and not all objects with the same name.
2

2
This means that now, if you really want the 'punch douchebag' command to work to punch a player, you can make that happen. The world is your oyster. ('tag all players with douchebag'!)
2

2
NOTE: Tagging objects, like weapons, may sometimes tag all instances of that object, and other times - like if it's modified, or has some sort of unique quality - it will tag only that particular object. The tagging system should be able to figure out what makes sense in the context of your command, but if it doesn't, complain. (The tag system is kind of new.)
